Can you give a short explanation of, what strips/fans are?

> I could imagine,
> that a pre- processing step could analyze an object and
> create more objects with reduced precision, maybe
> several of them. This would work quite similar than
> mipmapping for textures, so if an object is drawn at far
> distance, the low-polygon object is taken.

I've been thinking about this for a while. I started to
think about, how level of detail is handled in old games
like Frontier (Elite II) and F29-Retaliator. That is just
surface detail, but an object seem to consist of an
overall structure and then some detail.
(I'm thinking about putting it all into some kind of
super-object, opposite having several version of the same
object.)

Now, let's think about a cylinder. (It could be part of an
arm or a cannon.)

At close range, we would like it to be nice round, so it
could be made of 24 polygons to go all around the
cylinder. If we inside that have 12 polygons, then 6 and
3, we can drop the outer parts, as the object go into the
distance. (The resulting 3 polygon version will look like
a triangle seen from the end of the cylinder.)

Or we could have a 16 polygon version with an 8, 4 and 2
polygon version inside. (The 2 polygon version is special
and will look like a cross from the end of the cylinder.
Good for missiles, I think. :) )

Now, the trick is to make our code, so we don't have to
deal with all those polygons at once. Only the polygons
seen should be calculated.

I hope, these ideas will stimulate other people to come up
with some really brilliant thoughts.

Bye
John Niclasen
Denmark.

