@node 07852.002
Subject: Re: Re: Reducing bus traffic
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Fri, 02 Jul 1999 11:49:50 +0200

Matt Sealey wrote:
> Think of a paper fan - that's a fan! A row of triangles side
> by side, sharing two vertices each upside down to the next
> one - so the top of the fan has a flat base, then a point,
> then a flat base - but looks just like a line.. it's hard to
> explain in text..
> 
> _______________
> /\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/
> ---------------------
> 
> Like that :)

Actually, you just described a triangle *strip*. That's a sequence of triangles
where consecutive triangles share two vertices. 

A triangle fan is a set of triangles that all share one common edge. 

    0
   /\
  /  \
 5|   |1
  |   |
 4 \  /2
    \/
    3

In this figure, a triangle fan would be defined by
(0,1,2), (0,2,3), (0,3,4), (0,4,5)

The same figure could be described using a triangle strip:
(0,5,1), (5,1,4), (1,4,2), (4,2,3)

In the fan example, all triangles share common vertex 0.
In the strip example, each triangle shares the last two vertices from the
previous triangle.

Warp3D's API functions W3D_DrawTriangleFan and W3D_DrawTriangleStrip know about
these particuliarities, but the order in which these vertices must be specified
is cruical. If you want to draw a fan, you have to pass in the vertices as
0,1,2,3,4,5. If you are drawing a strip, you have to input them in order
0,5,1,4,2,3.

Regards, Hans-Joerg.

