>methods can be combined. I got very good results, when using face size
>toghether with searching for coplanar faces. But the best in my opinion is
>the Garland method.

I haven't read (or at least, I don't remember it) Garlands paper. But the
others that I know or  use coplaner, face size, and deformation cost to
determine best choice. but so far the ones that do a good job (on say 5000
recudes to 200) take 10 mins to 2 hrs on a P2-300. The ones that do
real-time reduction do well until about 500-600 polys whereafter the
objects begins to deteriorate. Still, none of them do (even the more
complex ones) do as good of a job as an artist. I think the best would be
the artist doing 2 or 3 versions and a redux engine inerpolate between the
artist versions. All you would need to do is link the polygons from the
lowest count to the groups of polys in the next higher count. THis was you
can completely control the quality with a low cost. It will also be easier
to implement a morphing engine to eliminate poping as well as better
control over texturemap coords, which can also me morphed.

