@node 07860.002
Subject: Strip/Fan generation
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Sat, 10 Jul 1999 14:51:51 +0200

Hi

As mentioned during the discussion about polygon reduction, the best
way to improve the situation around the slow bus systems is to use
triangle strips/fans. Unfortunately lots of games don't use them,
probably because earlier versions of various 3D API's didn't have
proper support for them.

In the case a game doesn't support strips/fans it would help a lot,
if the objects would be converted to maximize strip/fan usage. What
we need is such a converter, which tries to assemble triangle strips/fans
out of objects, which don't have any strip/fan related structure.

If anyone has a good link to algorithms, which do that, please provide
them. If there shouldn't exist a good generic algorithm, then it would
be very useful if anyone would attempt to write one.

Such an algorithm would have to deal with objects, where there is
absolutely no strip/fan related structure, where the triangles are
in no specific order, and where shared edges even aren't really
shared. The algorithm would have to make shared edges really shared
(by searching for identical vertices and migrate one vertex to
the other) and then to find triangle strips resp. fans.

I am right now writing some quick hack-style algorithm, which I would
like to use for my current project, but this is no good base for
a generic approach. I have figured out, that such an algorithm is far
from beeing trivial at all, if the goal should be to find the longest
strips/fans there are. Additionally I currently neglect fans, as it
would make the algorithm even more complicated.

One problem of this algorithm is how to find a good starting point for
a strip. There must be a rule, how to find a good starting triangle
(to avoid finding two strips, which would actually fit together)
then how to find the starting edge which should lead to the largest
strip. Additionally care must be taken, not to find crossing strips/
fans, which would cause triangles to be drawn multiple times.

Such a generic strip/fan generator would be of good use for porting
games to the AMIGA, which use older 3D API's not supporting strips/fans
at all. It is also essential to support the coming Voodoo1 hardware
solution, as the Z3 bus is going to be the major bottleneck.

