Hi

>In particular, I asked on the PML about porting parts of P96 to PPC in a
>special library so that PPC apps could avoid a couple of context
>swicthes just to so screen sycnronisation or double/tripple buffering.
>The answere was what I expect (and what I hoped for): if anyone wants to
>do it the sources will be made available to them.

>Actually, I am surprised no one has bothered to take up this task yet,

I an not surprised. It is far from beeing trivial to add *usable* PPC
support to the RTG systems. If an RTG system is present in both 68K
and PPC parts, then synchronisation is required between them, so that
no conflicts can happen, and this isn't easy, it would be necessary
to use MP-secure polling-based semaphores to do that. And then there
are the data structures accessed by both the 68K and the PPC part,
and performing synchronisation *without* doing any context switches
or cache flushes is lethal.

There are plently of problems and potential sources of slowdown just to
avoid a few contextswitches which contribute maybe to 1-2ms of the
performance of an application (5-10 times less for the next hardware
generation). Not to speak about the complexity to write a 68K-PPC-mixed
application, even based on an existing design, which wasn't built for
such an architecture (and in the case of P96 lots of code is 68K
assembler).

Most functions of a RTG system aren't suitable anyway for beeing ported
to PPC. Functions which copy stuff to VRAM won't run faster on the PPC
than on the 68K, other functions simply don't have any considerable
arithmetic load.

I strongly believe that most people take the context switching problem
much too serious. In a game-like application it is possible to reduce
them so that they don't play an important role anymore. For other
seriously OS-based applications it's anyway futile to attempt to
port them to PPC and no hack/patch-based addition will ever change
that.

>as porting certain parts of the OS to PPC would be a major advance for
>PPC, and the shear number of 68k replacement patches of parts of the OS
>suggest it must be possible even without original sources.

I doubt very much, as PPC-based patches are a completely different story
than 68K-based patches. Remember, the entry points into the current
libraries are always 68K-based, so there is no way to avoid context
switches, unless entry points for PPC are there, which would imply
a new library, which would have to be integrated some kind into the
68K-based implementations.

It's far too complicated and doesn't give enough advantage to justify
that.

