@node 07862.002
Subject: Re: Overclocking ppc card
From: Paul Qureshi <paul@mc68k.demon.co.uk>
Date: Sun, 11 Jul 1999 17:02:17 +0000

On 10-Jul-99, Sam Jordan wrote:

[RTG for PPC]

>> Actually, I am surprised no one has bothered to take up this task
>> yet,

> I an not surprised. It is far from beeing trivial to add *usable* PPC
> support to the RTG systems. If an RTG system is present in both 68K
> and PPC parts, then synchronisation is required between them, so that
> no conflicts can happen, and this isn't easy, it would be necessary
> to use MP-secure polling-based semaphores to do that. And then there
> are the data structures accessed by both the 68K and the PPC part,
> and performing synchronisation *without* doing any context switches
> or cache flushes is lethal.

It all depends how far you take it. Take screen sync for instance. It
requires some hardware access (via the relevant chip library for P96) to
find the VBL. All you need to make it PPC is a special version of the
chip library for PPC, and the modify the 68k library to use an external
semaphore for data needed by the cut down PPC chip library. The PPC chip
lib would only support one fuction, frame sync, so it shouldn't be too
hard IMHO (I don't know the specifics of P96, correct me if I'm wrong).

Next, make a PPC picasso96api.library. In this version, only support
frame sycnronisation. Don't make it patch into the graphics.library, it
will be up to PPC programs to call it themselves indead.

I don't claim to be an expert on VGA hardware, but from what I have read
it doesn't seem to be too hard. It seems you basically have to poll a
register for most chipsets I have seen, and that can be done easily for
PPC.

> There are plently of problems and potential sources of slowdown just
> to avoid a few contextswitches which contribute maybe to 1-2ms of the
> performance of an application (5-10 times less for the next hardware
> generation). Not to speak about the complexity to write a
> 68K-PPC-mixed application, even based on an existing design, which
> wasn't built for such an architecture (and in the case of P96 lots of
> code is 68K assembler).

Well, while it may be a small gain and may cause a few headaches to
impliment, I see there are Amiga VNC clients still in development so my
faith in Amiga coders taking on tricky tasks is still there :)

I think it will be interesting to see the G3 cards. With them using 68k
emulation, a PPC OS seems the next logical step. 3D APIs seem to be
ready for this change, but quite how RTG and the interface with it that
3D APIs use will change is something that will cause many problems I'm
sure.

> Most functions of a RTG system aren't suitable anyway for beeing
> ported to PPC. Functions which copy stuff to VRAM won't run faster on
> the PPC than on the 68K, other functions simply don't have any
> considerable arithmetic load.

Perhaps I didn't state my idea very well.. I was only thinking of
porting parts that could be of use to real time applications every
rendered frame, such as VBL sync and (that much harder) multibuffering.
This would also not be patched into graphics.library, but be separate.

>> as porting certain parts of the OS to PPC would be a major advance
>> for PPC, and the shear number of 68k replacement patches of parts of
>> the OS suggest it must be possible even without original sources.

> I doubt very much, as PPC-based patches are a completely different
> story than 68K-based patches. Remember, the entry points into the
> current libraries are always 68K-based, so there is no way to avoid
> context switches, unless entry points for PPC are there, which would
> imply a new library, which would have to be integrated some kind into
> the 68K-based implementations.

I think for now parallel libraries may be the answere. Take the problem
with PPC datatypes. They could be speeded up by not using 68k for disk
access, so a dosppc.library that had similar functions to dos.library
would benfit them a lot.

Anyway, its a bit OT now and as you say no one has the time or patience
to look into it, so unless anyone has any ideas how it relates to 3D
graphics..?

Regards,
Paul
