@node 07860.007
Subject: Re: Strip/Fan generation
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Sun, 11 Jul 1999 00:15:41 +0200

Am 10-Jul-99 schrieb Hans-Joerg Frieden:

Hi

>> One problem of this algorithm is how to find a good starting point for
>> a strip. There must be a rule, how to find a good starting triangle

>I would suspect that a good starting point would be to search the vertex
>that is part of the least triangles. I would suspect that this vertex (or
>better, the triangle it belongs to) would be some kind of natural
>candidate for the start/end of a triangle strip...

>Likewise, the vertex with the highest trianle count would be a good
>candidate for triangle fans...

>Just a thought... :)

More thoughts appreciated. My initial attempt to write a strip-generator
failed, because it took 20 seconds on my 604e/180 to perform the
calculations for all objects (>500 objects, lots with 50-100 triangles),
and it took me lots of hours to write the code. One problem is to
find adjacent triangles, especially if triangles have shared edges
with nonshared vertices Using the brute-force approach it would
be necessary to check n^2 triangles, therefore some hashtable
appraoch is necessary. But even this didn't help here...

One problem was, that often there are several possibilities how
a strip can be generated based on the first triangle. If the
first triangle is stored with vertex-order v1,v2,v3 a completely
different strip is generated as if the same triangle is stored
with vertex-order v1,v3,v2. If neglecting this, the efficiency
of the strip-generator goes down, as very often short strips
are found, although there exist much longer ones.

I think it's a real challenge to write a good and fast strip/fan
generator, so anybody who likes challenges is welcome to face it.

bye
