Hello Sam,

On 10-Jul-99, Sam Jordan wrote:
> More thoughts appreciated. 

I dont know any hardware details of the triangle handling within the
Virge/P2/Voodoo - do any of them have on-board vertex registers? If so,
this would help cut down bus usage by caching some vertices on the chip,
then the 3d software can intelligently use this in the uploading of the
triangle strips.

> One problem was, that often there are several possibilities how
> a strip can be generated based on the first triangle. If the
> first triangle is stored with vertex-order v1,v2,v3 a completely
> different strip is generated as if the same triangle is stored
> with vertex-order v1,v3,v2.

I guess it would require some form of "look ahead testing" within the build
strip loop.


The following details the basis of how to build a strip from a list of
triangles (someone described this to me some time ago - so I am working from
memory here, but I believe that there is a research paper available on the
'net where this idea is taken from - sorry, I dont have the URL...)  

Firstly, take the list of triangles and mark them as "not searched".
To find the best starting point for the strip, try searching through the
list of triangles looking for the one with the least number of adjoining
triangles. (Depending on the model shape, there might not be an obvious
ideal place to start from)

From the starting triangle, now try to build the strip -
If there are two adjoining "not searched" triangles, continue to build the
strip in a counter-clockwise direction but push the other adjoining
triangles into a list of possible locations for a strip restart.

If there are no adjoining "not searched" triangles, it cannot continue with
the strip, therefore it must restart a new strip from the first "not
searched" triangle in the list of possible locations, and then clears the
list.
 

If there are no "not searched" triangles in the list of possible locations,
then we might be in a corner of the object, so the strip building process
needs to be restarted at a new starting point in the list of triangles.
When choosing the new starting point, try to pick a triangle with the
smallest number of "not searched" adjoining triangles.


No doubt I have missed something from this... Perhaps your own strip
generator uses something like this method?

