@node 07866.019
Subject: Re: Genesis3D
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Fri, 16 Jul 1999 16:58:12 +0200

Filip Doksansky wrote:
>  WOW ! Maybe you can help me - how is solved in Lith engine lightning in
> hardware rendering ? Software renderers uses often surface cacheing and
> lightmapping (as I'm doing that) but what about hardware rendering ?

Sorry, three letters: N-D-A... I am not allowed to tell you :(

> I saw some examples, where it's done by two pass rendering, where is
> second texture as lightmap (much smaller of course). Is there some
> faster solution ? What about software rendering of lightmap for WHOLE
> scene ? Isn't it more effective in the case engine hasn't zero overdraw
> i hardware version ?

You can do lightmapping in two passes if the chip supports the right blending
mode, which isn't the case on both the Virge and the Permedia2. On neat chips
like the RivaTNT or the Savage 4, you can do single pass multitexturing, where
this is done in a single, dual-pipelined texel fetch from two sources. The
Savage 4 has an extensive set of register bits where you can influence how the
first texture modifies the second - very neat, and very fast. Dual pass
rendering is the only solution I know of, except for texture caching. 

I think you can, to a limited degree, simulate lightmapping with a dual pass
rendering on both chips, but you will have to limit yourself to monochromatic
white light. In the first pass you draw normally, and in the second pass, you
draw the lightmap with alpha blending modes enabled (W3D_ALPHA,
W3D_ONE_MINUS_ALPHA). The key is that your lightmap needs to be of type
W3D_I8A8, where the intensities are set to all black, and the Alpha value is
the reverse of the light value, i.e alpha=1 means the pixel is completely
shadowed, while alpha=0 means the pixel is completely the original colour. Note
that this only can darken the wall, not light it up. I have never tried this,
but I think it should work...

Texture caching works reasonably fast if you have a fast memory interface and a
fast bus, since it tends to invalidate the on-card texture cache very
frequently. Since textures tend to be large, this is a problem for both the
68060 memory cache and the slow Z3 bus - a PCI interface would work miracles.

Shogo actually has a mode where you can switch off lightmapping entirely. If
your polygons aren't too big, you can use gouraud shading only. If they get too
big, you can subdivide them into smaller polygons, and take the color for the
vertices you generate by a lookup into the light map. This actualy works quite
reaonable. and the result looks only slightly worse than the lightmapped
version overall - if you like, I can send you two screenshots to compare...

