I certainly agree, that there are tons of games which are comparable
concerning violence and the presentation of it. I started to mention
this problem as I don't see why it is really necessary to concentrate
on most violent games when talking about games to be ported. On the
other hand I know that sales seem to be somehow proportional to the
violence factor. I also know that this isn't the fault of the game
manufacturers, they only deliver what the majority of people want to
have. It also seems that shooting at people becomes most enjoyable
the more realistic the game looks like. We aren't that far away from
a quality which will look exactly like reality, additionally games
will probably in future support 3d-glasses. And then the question is
left open, where is the difference between the virtual world and
reality anymore. The only difference will be, that the player knows
that the virtual world is virtual and the reality is real. In other
words: shooting at persons becomes something funny and the only barrier
which prevents people from doing so is, that the rational part of
the brain says 'killing people is something very bad'. But if people
would be able to disable the rational part of the brain, they would
probably also enjoy killing people in the real world in the same way,
because only the emotional part of the brain would be active, and the
emotional part has already enjoyed killing thousands of virtual people,
which look the same like real people.

Violence at some degree isn't really a problem, as long as the virtual
world differs much from reality and if the presentation isn't too
tasteless. And in my case watching at the comrade's PC playing one single
level of KP was really enough and I probably didn't watch the parts
which you mention as problematic. On the other hand I accept that other
people's threshold is at another level.

To come back to my original point: It would be very sad in my eyes, if
the AMIGA people would choose games with very high violence factor as
next games beeing ported, if there are enough alternatives around.

bye
