> topic so I'll just stop right now...

Now that we're living in societies it's good that people are starting
to question whether the behaviour that got us to the top of the food
chain is now appropriate or sustainable. I guess if you think about
it it's a sign of evolutionary progress, but expecting millions of
years of evolution to switch directions overnight is really asking
a bit much. Rather than seeing humans as stupid, I'm actually
pretty amazed at how adaptable we are on the whole. The fact is,
civilization has been remarkably successful in helping to supress
our predatory nature using a combination of meeting basic needs,
keeping us busy with rituals and mundane routines like going off
to work each day, and channeling our natural aggression into
other areas like sport with the occasional steam-vent involving
the odd all-out war here and there. While it might be too little
to some, I tend to think that's what we'll be doing for the
next few millions years at least.

