"more comments"... SCNR :)

OK, here's my impression of the AmigaNG, as seen on the show. They where
talking about their new system "AmigaObjects", which is kind of a
completely object-oriented approach to writing an operating system, or
rather, build on top of an operating system (they specifically mentioned
that AmigaObject will be abstract enough to be build on any os, including
but not limited to QNX). Basically, it regards each service a computer may
offer as an object - examples included disk files, windows, memory, but
also more complex stuff like TV tuners, DVD drives and other stuff. All AO
are networked, meaning they know how to communicate internally or over a
network, which also includes wireless networks.

One of the example was that the wireless tablet (kind of a PADD like in
Star Trek) could be used to watch TV. For that, it would require an object
that has a TV tuner, one that can decode the video stream, and one that
can display it. Only the display object would reside on the tablet, and
connect to a TV tuner and decoder over the network. 

Other examples that Havermose mentioned where freezing the contents of an
object (his example was about a word processor) and transferring it to a
new location where you could unfreeze it and continue. While this is
basically possible with more traditional handling (save it to a file),
this is just one example where AmigaObject is much more elegant, and most
notably, the application object (the word processor in this case) need not
implement anything for that since it inherits the base class.

The hardware for their MCC is quite exciting. They are using two ATI
chips, the ATI Rage Theater for video input/output (it can capture and
display PAL and NTSC video) and a the new chip for display of raster and
3D graphics. This chip can also be used to drive RGB flatpanel displays.
There's quite a lot of connectivity built-in, for example the wireless
2.3 GHz network (I think it was 2.3 G), ethernet, USB etc. They didn't
mention their CPU choice, although you might have heard of the video they
showed that mentioned Transmeta (it was in the list of tech partners,
right behind Sun and Corel). While this might mean nothing (they admitted
they where in talks with Linus Torvalds), I would like to think that was
an inofficial admittance that the Transmeta will be the next CPU (I think
it was Havermose that said later "I cannot comment on the Transmeta
rumor"). Transmeta is like Area 51 (or Groom Lake, as you like), no one
knows anything about it really, but everyone talks about it. Would be a
real smash hit if this is true, the hype around the chip alone would make
the competition shiver... :)

Regards, Hans-Joerg.

