It was written on the DI homepages for quite some time, that WO2097 is
3d hardware only resp. Warp3D only, in addition to PPC-only. The text
was written by myself, as I did major parts of the porting work, especially
all the graphics and 3d stuff.

A 603e is the *bottom-end* CPU for this game, as it is a very
CPU-intensive game, additionally its polygon count is very high,
which leads to high bus-pressure when full details are enabled.

The speed of the game also depends on the resolution chosen and on the
detail settings. These details can be adjusted very much, but I don't
know what the persons demonstrating the game did choose concerning
details and graphics quality. The AMIGA version provides the possibility
to have a bigger view distance than the PC/PSX version did, which leads
to nice graphics quality and to good scalability of the game concerning
future hardware. The AMIGA version will also provide other exclusive
features like fogging, gamma correction or mipmapping/trilinear filtering
(if supported by hardware).

Besides that I'm almost sure that the AMIGA version will be the most
efficient port of all, as it was optimized very much, many core parts
of the code were rewritten. The PC version also requires a fast CPU and
a good 3d card to achieve an acceptable frame rate. The minimum requirement
for the PC version is something like Pentium166/Voodoo1, and the other
person working on WO2097 had the pleasure to test the game on such a config,
and it wasn't running fast, and additionally very unevenly, leading to
much harder ship control.

Finally I know myself, that it's generally wrong to demonstrate a game
on low-end hardware (I said that to Stuart Walker, too), because of people
finding the game slow without knowing about the circumstances, but apparently
they didn't have any other option.

